docs.abstract: Scholars said they would not hold classes or lectures on Wednesday, and leading journals and scientific associations said they would not announce most breakthroughs.
docs.snippet: Scholars said they would not hold classes or lectures on Wednesday, and leading journals and scientific associations said they would not announce most breakthroughs.
docs.lead_paragraph: Galvanized by the reaction to the killing of George Floyd and continued reports that minority researchers feel marginalized and disrespected, almost 6,000 scientists and academicians said they would participate in a one-day strike on Wednesday.

headline.main: For a Day, Scientists Pause Science to Confront Racism
headline.print_headline: No Classes, No Meetings, No Reports: To Battle Racism, Scientists Halt Science for a Day

docs.abstract: Amid widespread protests against police brutality and the coronavirus pandemic, a determined electorate pushed turnout past 2016 levels.
docs.snippet: Amid widespread protests against police brutality and the coronavirus pandemic, a determined electorate pushed turnout past 2016 levels.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — As the nation remained gripped by widespread protests against police brutality and systemic racism, black and Hispanic women won elections in multiple states on Tuesday while Representative Steve King, a nine-term congressman with a long history of racist remarks, was ousted in a Republican primary in Iowa.

headline.main: Historic Wins for Women of Color as Nation Protests Systemic Racism
headline.print_headline: A Day of Historic Wins For Women of Color

byline.original: By Reid J. Epstein, Jennifer Medina and Nick Corasaniti

docs.abstract: Black leaders regularly fail to rise to the challenges that confront young people.
docs.snippet: Black leaders regularly fail to rise to the challenges that confront young people.
docs.lead_paragraph: Young black people have exploded in rebellion over the grotesque killing of George Floyd. We are now witnessing the broadest protest movement in American history. And yet the response of black elected officials has been cautious and uninspired.

docs.abstract: After the killing of George Floyd, a small Minneapolis fund that is paying bail for protesters saw a huge influx of donations.
docs.snippet: After the killing of George Floyd, a small Minneapolis fund that is paying bail for protesters saw a huge influx of donations.
docs.lead_paragraph: A small Minneapolis bail fund has received millions of dollars in funding from people after the killing of George Floyd, a black man who died on Memorial Day after a white police officer pinned him to the ground with his knee.

headline.main: How a Minnesota Bail Fund Raised $20 Million

docs.abstract: These shows may fill in some of the gaps left by your school curriculum and deepen your understanding of what’s happening now.
docs.snippet: These shows may fill in some of the gaps left by your school curriculum and deepen your understanding of what’s happening now.
docs.lead_paragraph: Even with half of the year left, it’s already clear 2020 will be one for the history books. A deadly pandemic, economic collapse, and a reckoning on race and police brutality will ensure that this year will be remembered as one of seismic change. And in times of uncertainty and upheaval, one of the best ways to understand the future is to look to the past.

headline.print_headline: Listening to the Past Is Kind of Perfect

docs.abstract: Corrections that appeared in print on Thursday, June 4, 2020.
docs.snippet: Corrections that appeared in print on Thursday, June 4, 2020.
docs.lead_paragraph: An article on Wednesday about protests against police brutality evolving into a nationwide movement with diverse interests and tactics misidentified the location of an episode at a protest in Baltimore. It was outside City Hall, not outside the governor’s mansion.

docs.abstract: We asked an art historian who studies the destruction of cultural heritage.
docs.snippet: We asked an art historian who studies the destruction of cultural heritage.
docs.lead_paragraph: Confederate statues and statues of other historical figures, including slave traders and Christopher Columbus, are being toppled throughout the U.S. and around the world this week — an outgrowth of weeks of protests over entrenched racism in the United States, reignited by the killing of George Floyd in police custody.

headline.main: What Does It Mean to Tear Down a Statue?

docs.abstract: A majority of American voters support demonstrations on police brutality, and many see the president as ill-equipped on racial justice.
docs.snippet: A majority of American voters support demonstrations on police brutality, and many see the president as ill-equipped on racial justice.
docs.lead_paragraph: A majority of American voters support the demonstrations against police brutality and racial injustice that have roiled the country over the past month, embracing ideas about bias within the criminal justice system and the persistence of systemic racism that are central tenets of the Black Lives Matter movement, according to a new national poll of registered voters by The New York Times and Siena College.

headline.main: How Trump and the Black Lives Matter Movement Changed White Voters’ Minds
headline.print_headline: White Voters’ Views on Race Show Change

byline.original: By Astead W. Herndon and Dionne Searcey

docs.abstract: Economic equality is crucial to racial equality. But at nearly every stage of their lives, black Americans have less than whites.
docs.snippet: Economic equality is crucial to racial equality. But at nearly every stage of their lives, black Americans have less than whites.
docs.lead_paragraph: We cannot quantify the injustice of a white policeman holding his knee on the neck of a handcuffed, dying black man. And mere numbers cannot fully express the power imbalance involved in the deaths of George Floyd and too many others like him.

headline.main: The Stark Racial Inequity of Personal Finances in America
headline.print_headline: Quantifying The Inequity Many Face In Finance

byline.original: By Ron Lieber and Tara Siegel Bernard

docs.abstract: Most officers of color share the protesters’ mission to defeat racism, but the unrest has reminded the officers that they are still often seen as the enemy.
docs.snippet: Most officers of color share the protesters’ mission to defeat racism, but the unrest has reminded the officers that they are still often seen as the enemy.
docs.lead_paragraph: Edwin Raymond, a black lieutenant in the Police Department, heard racial insults — “Sellout!” and “Uncle Tom!” — rising above protesters’ chants as he helped to control the crowds at recent demonstrations in Brooklyn against police brutality and racism.

headline.main: How Black N.Y.P.D. Officers Really Feel About the Floyd Protesters
headline.print_headline: Torn Between Two Worlds: Black Officers at New York Protests

byline.original: By Ashley Southall and Edgar Sandoval
